The online education industry is suddenly awash with teachers and students

Will have a profound impact on the future of Chinese education

The "Normandy landing" of online education

Staff Writer / Su Jiade

Published in the 938th issue of China Newsweek on March 9,2020

Into March, many schools still do not see the hope of opening.

Education is one of the most widespread industries affected by the epidemic. The start of the school year has been postponed several times and there is still no clear timetable. The Ministry of Education issued a notice on Jan. 27, postponing the start of the spring semester. On February 28, the Ministry of Education issued a notice again, asking that "the starting time of universities, primary schools, kindergartens and so on should continue to be postponed in principle. "

That means more than 300 million students and teachers across the country will not be able to go back to school. According to the National Statistics Bulletin on the development of Education published by the Ministry of Education in July 2019, in 2018 there were 276 million students enrolled in all levels and types of education, and 16,728,500 full-time teachers at all levels and types of schools nationwide, of those, 150 million are in compulsory education.

In response to the delay, the Ministry of Education is to provide a solution: the use of network platform, suspended without suspension. The "No suspension, no suspension" notice directly ignited the online education boom, hundreds of millions of teachers and students across the country poured into Internet classrooms. More than 10 Million Teachers Have Become Webmasters, and more than 200 million students have become "fans. ".

"This is a large-scale educational experiment, which is a big step forward for online education, " China Association for Promoting Democracy Zhu Yongxin, deputy secretary-general of the Standing Committee of the National Committee of the CPPCC, told China Newsweek.

Online education may bring about a "Normandy landing" for Chinese education, opening up a second front in addition to traditional education.

"Beach Fighting" online course

On Feb. 27, Han Jinyu, a high school sophomore in Xiangyang, Hubei Province, sat at his desk at home and watched the teacher's lecture through an online education tool, the teacher on the other end of the network answers in real time. This way of learning, he has been two weeks, more than a year from the college entrance examination, he has entered the "countdown. ".

For Han kim-woo, the winter vacation was particularly long. Usually this time, he should sit in the classroom to listen to the teacher's lecture, after class back to the bedroom and roommates chat and play. However, the new crown pneumonia epidemic swept across the country, in order to prevent and control the epidemic, people had to stay at home to fight the "epidemic" , the normal rhythm of life has been disrupted.

"At this time, the advantages and convenience of online education over offline institutions are clearly demonstrated, and many parents have turned their eyes to online education, " Li Guoxun, executive director of the VIPKID Academy, an off-campus Training Organization, told China Newsweek.

The nail used by Han Jinyu is one of the most popular software for this online education APP. Nail was originally under the banner of Alibaba's office software, during the epidemic, the Emergency Online "home class" function. Fang Yongxin, head of the Nail Education Line, told China News weekly that more than 50 million students were already using the nail in classes online in mid-february. By contrast, it took five years to reach 200 million users between 2015 and the first half of 2019.

Nail "Home Class" program is very powerful, covering online teaching, online submission and correction of homework, online exams and other applications, and free for use by the country's primary and secondary schools. However, these "powerful functions" have been protested by many primary and secondary school students, who generally report that vacation break time is being commandeered, forced to download registration, nail invasion of personal privacy too much. The students went so far as to give the APP market a one-star "thumbs-up" that their ratings, pegged at the APP store, dropped from 4.9 to 1.3 almost overnight. Fang Yongxin said he understood the low grade, and his daughter even wrote a lot of suggestions for nailing. "I carefully read many children's posts and wrote them with great talent. "

The sudden outbreak has pushed the fast forward button for the entire online education industry. Not only Alibaba, but other Internet giants are also rushing into the education market, competing for huge amounts of traffic. BYTEDANCE and 50 educational institutions provide free lessons to primary and secondary school students across the country; Iqiyi has joined hands with other online schools to create a team of free live-streaming teachers; and tencent offers 20,000-minute free lessons in video.

Eight years in the making, K-12 is the country's first Unicorn Company in the field of online education, ape-assisted online education. In response to the outbreak, 356 lecturers, 457 teaching assistants and 151 technicians were mobilized, starting February 3, large-scale free-to-air classes will be offered. A record 1.23 million high school students took part in a nationwide million-person online test launched on Feb. 15 by the ape-assisted online education APP.

Established Education and training institutions have also introduced free large-class live broadcast and broadcast classes. Good Future, New Oriental and other institutions through the donation of courses, services, the establishment of education funds and other forms to compete for flow. New Oriental Chairman Yu Minhong also ordered mobile phone brackets, lighting and other live broadcast equipment, in the fast-hand platform to start his own live broadcast debut, the incarnation of "Internet celebrities" to teach students and parents.

Within a week of the outbreak, New Oriental moved 87 campuses, subsidiaries and nearly 2 million students online, Yu Minhong said in an interview. During this process, the server expanded several times, the three platforms under the total capacity of 10 million people, the overall smooth operation, the final drop rate was controlled at about 3% .

Orient univision is a new oriental online education company, the main primary and secondary schools online small interactive live broadcast courses. Zhu Yu, CEO of Orient Univision, told China Newsweek: "The traffic effect this time is far more than the one billion RMB spent by the major online education companies last summer. If the figures are used, it would be equivalent to saving Internet education institutions nearly 100 billion yuan in promotion costs."

On capital market, online education also becomes"Darling". Netease, which just went public in the U.S. , surged on Feb. 7 and 10, rising more than 80 percent in just two trading days, while other online education stocks in China and Taiwan also continued to rise.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Students attend a class on Feb. 10 via a live cloud system at Fruit Lake Primary School in Wuhan. On the same day, Wuhan Primary and Secondary Schools (secondary vocational schools) in accordance with the teaching plan, to carry out online teaching. Photographer Hubei Daily, Tian Yue

Technological "hard-hitting"

At 10 a.m. on Feb. 2, while the Tianjin huaying school was on the third day of its winter vacation class, the live streaming software suddenly appeared on a large scale, and lasted about 40 minutes, Cottonwood said. "The first class is not over yet. The next class is going to start. At this time, there was a scramble for resources, and there was a situation where a teacher, Cottonwood, who wanted to start classes early, couldn't get in,"Liu Shucheng, deputy principal of huaying school, told China News Weekly, at the same time many live broadcast platform also appeared different degree of problem.

When hundreds of millions of students and teachers flood the live streaming platform, it's easy to flood the dam. "The situation is beyond our imagination. Only about 3,000 institutions registered in the background during the Lunar New Year. If it weren't for our very complicated registration process, the number of registrations would be tens of thousands in a day, " Yiou education said on its official wechat account, detailing the experience of this special period.

Wing Gull Education is an online classroom service for educational institutions. During the outbreak, back-office traffic began to skyrocket, with a peak of more than 1.6 million students logging on in a single day, and more than 350,000 students online, and before the outbreak, the platform was 30,000 at its peak. In addition to offline institutions, a number of public schools are also coming, including Peking University, Beijing Normal University, the Chinese University of Science and Technology, Renmin University Affiliated High School, Beijing No.4 High School, 101 Middle School and so on.

For this urgent response to these customers, Wing Gull Education to do everything possible to expand the system. But because the expansion speed is too fast, the system stability drops sharply, "the old user scolds us to be greedy for money to sign a contract too much, the system is not too stable, the service level drops precipitously. "

In the online education industry, small and medium-sized institutions often use third-party online education or live streaming systems such as wing Gull Education. The sudden surge in user demand has overwhelmed these third-party systems. "If new oriental does move more than a million students directly into third-party systems, their systems won't be able to carry them because they will carry a lot of business from outside institutions, " Yu Minhong said. It means that all of us have no platform at home and New Oriental may go out of business."

How to nail up to 50 million concurrent person-times? Fang Yongxin, relying on the full support of Alibaba Cloud, when the initial flow peak arrived, nail nail two hours to expand the capacity of more than 10,000 servers. In the past, Alibaba Cloud has added a total of 100,000 cloud servers to nail's network. "without these machines, it would be nice to have 10 million people in the classroom at once, " he said

"without cloud computing, online education companies would never be able to cope with the explosion of business volume, " Jiang Nan, an industry architect for Alibaba cloud intelligent online education, told China News Week, some customers require resources for the next day to be ready in one day, and not just for capacity expansion. It also puts a lot of pressure on Alibaba Cloud when more than one client comes forward at the same time.

From early February to now, nail every two or three days to go through a product iteration, from live Cottonwood, even wheat effect, voice quality is constantly optimized. Fang Yongxin introduction: "At the beginning of the discovery of Cottonwood problem, thought that is not enough expansion, Alibaba Cloud has done a number of large-scale expansion, but there are user feedback use is not free. ". Later, our analysis found that 80% to 90% of the users were caused by the differentiated network environment, as well as problems with computers, mobile phones and other hardware devices,"Fang Yongxin said, citing an example, the "jitter" problem during voice calls may be caused by the different network types and bandwidth of the two parties, which are hard to optimize immediately.

Not every agency can get as much support as a spike. "We have to limit the flow of traffic in order to keep the system stable, " Yi'ou said. "The plan is to build a new, very large-scale communications network to accommodate tens of millions of students, but it will take a long time. "

These technical experience problems have also attracted the attention of the Ministry of Education. The Ministry of Education said in an interview: to ensure the normal operation of the network is to ensure the basic premise of online teaching. Due to the large number of students in primary and secondary schools in China, the basic network conditions vary widely, and the network congestion occurred during the same period of delay in starting school. All over the industry and information departments and network operations to increase the coordination of enterprises, actively strive for support. To adapt to local conditions, proceed from the actual, according to the local network, service capacity, distribution of students to do a good analysis and judgment, targeted guidance "wrong peak" log on the Internet.

Under the National Network Class Pattern, some new questions surface. On the morning of Feb. 29, Li Mou Min, a 14-year-old girl in the third year of junior middle school in Dengzhou, Henan Province, could not afford to buy a mobile phone and attend online school classes on time because her family was poor and she swallowed a large amount of her mother's medication for mental illness, according to china.com.cn. "affected by the outbreak, after years, the Li siblings could only take Internet classes at home, " the report said. Although his father, Li Handang, scraped together a neighbor to help him buy a smartphone on the Internet, he didn't have much time for his sister and brother because he only had one phone, so he missed a lot of homework. At the same time, he also had to face the doubts of his teachers and classmates. He couldn't think straight for a moment and chose to swallow his mother's medicine."

Many children in rural and remote mountainous areas are likely to be excluded from "online classes" because their families can not afford to buy smartphones, tablets or mobile phone traffic, resulting in school dropouts at Special Times. In some areas where there is no internet coverage, tencent's deep web reported in an article titled Online Lessons In Remote Mountain Areas: Families Save traffic for their children, and some learn while herding sheep, "Go against the network" , find the signal has become this "super-long winter vacation" many rural and remote mountain children learn every day, "compulsory course" one. Some children need to walk hundreds of meters or even kilometers to the village branch or the edge of a cliff to get online lessons.

How to prevent students from being blocked out of online courses due to poverty has raised new issues for the online education industry and education departments.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The existential crisis of offline institutions

On January 20, when Li Zhong, the head of huaying school, heard Academician Zhong Nanshan's statement about the "human-to-human transmission" of NCP, he immediately felt the seriousness of the situation, and after the SARS period he was particularly sensitive to the epidemic.

Huaying school is a tianjin-based offline training institution with more than 20,000 students and more than 30 years of operation. "I said in the wechat group that the training institutions would probably have to suspend classes, and other management didn't think it was too far from Tianjin, " said Li Zhong, who was impressed by the life-and-death crisis many training institutions faced during the 2003 SARS outbreak, "A lot of training institutions have closed down because of refunds. ".

In response to the SARS suspension, Li Zhong recalled, he bought several CD ROMS on a temporary basis and distributed the teacher's lessons on a CD to students. The recorder worked around the clock, buying a second one when it broke down and eventually producing nearly 15,000 discs. To Li Zhong's surprise, the vast majority of parents did not refund their fees, but switched to summer tuition in Huaying, which saw a surge in student enrolments after the SARS outbreak.

2020 is the last year when huaying school joined elite education group. With the new pneumonia outbreak, Li Zhong was once again faced with an existential crisis and pressure to deliver results.

"All parts of the country are demanding that offline education and training institutions suspend classes one after another. For the leaders of offline education and training institutions, it is a choice whether to wait and see further, or to take active actions and move from offline to online, " said Zhu Yu, CEO of Orient youbroadcast, some offline institutions worry that if not good transfer, but will cause the loss of students. But do not transfer, the source of students will soon be online institutions snatched, offline institutions due to no income due to suspension, short-term cash flow will occur, the company failed.

"In any case, it's better to make a change than to sit back and do nothing, otherwise the new east, which has been around for nearly three decades, will collapse, " said Yu Minhong, who said the outbreak had prevented one million students from taking classes during the winter break, the livelihood of the eighty thousand teachers and staff was immediately in question, and New Oriental was forced to close its doors.

Compared with the new oriental such head training institutions, small and medium-sized institutions face much more severe challenges. More than 90 percent of out-of-school training institutions in 31 provinces, autonomous regions and municipalities across the country said they had a significant impact, according to a survey conducted from Feb. 7 to 14 by the Professional Committee on training and education of the China Association for Privately-run Education, at present, there are some difficulties or serious difficulties in the operation of the organization. Among the hardest hit offline training schools, 49.42 percent expect their revenues to fall by more than 50 percent from a year earlier.

"At the moment there is very little revenue, but the wages are still being paid and the rent is being paid. To put it bluntly, I've lost almost all my money in a year. The only thing we can do now is shoulder it, there is no other way,"Feng Haojie, principal of Jinglian Math School in Zhengzhou, Henan Province, told China News Weekly, if the outbreak persists and summer off-campus training season is affected, his school could face a major crisis.

But for off-line training institutions, the transformation of the line, the face of more than just cost issues. Thunderstorm capital focuses on education venture capital, "online education has its own business characteristics and competitive challenges, " Zhu Guoping, managing director, told China News Weekly. "You don't just go from offline to online and get a bonus. Quite a number of institutions used to being offline are difficult to adapt to, which has led to a reshuffle of training institutions."

In fact, even a company like ape coaching, which has been based on online education since its inception, has gone through an intense process of business model exploration. "from the beginning, the idea of 'products that provide continuous value to users have vitality' was very strong, and in the process, we gradually became more and more firm on 'education online' , " Shuaike, co-founder of Simian counseling, told China Newsweek

Many in the industry are predicting that the online education industry will accelerate its shake-out in spite of the surge in student numbers. In the decade before the outbreak, many online educational institutions were struggling to make money. Zhang Xi, founder of elite education, said publicly that "at least 60 percent of online education companies will fail within a year. "

The crisis at offline training institutions came earlier, with the IT vocational education, education for all, becoming the first to officially declare the brand "bankrupt" during the outbreak. On Feb. 6, the company announced that the Beijing campus would stop recruiting students and its employees would be laid off. On February 13, the online education brand "Mingxi Dayu" became the second educational institution to close down in 2020 due to a break in funding.

Education Chain Nghe Education was forced to take a pay cut across the board. Li Haoyang, the founder, said in a post on his friends' circle that he was "determined to be a bad guy, with 3.5% pay for all employees for five months, zero pay for the most core executives and half pay for a month" to ensure the company could "survive. ". He explained that in the epidemic, although online students increased, but most of the company's operating costs are free, Nghe currently has 320 million in cash on its education account, could have lived for two years, if you can only live for six months without an income.

The "Jobs question" of education

How many users will be able to survive the wave of free live courses? This is the biggest concern for the entire online education industry.

"Good Future" officials told China News weekly that as the epidemic eases, the public's demand for online classes will become more rational, and the quality of class content, rather than free, will be re-examined, "The deep cultivation of the curriculum content, technical support, teaching staff and other key links in education is still the key to enterprise competition. "

In January this year, the total number of users reached 400 million, it is understood that its conversion rate, retention rate is very high, even higher than most paid Internet products. Shuaike told China News weekly that the quality learning experience allows users to try and use it, and only when it is effective in improving their performance will they stay.

Li Guoxun, Executive Director of Vipkid Research Institute, said the specialty of the education industry is that it places great emphasis on learning effects. For online education to continue to develop, it is necessary to pay attention to the combination of educational resources and technology so that parents can see better teaching effects.

"The success of an online education platform depends on two basic capabilities: A high-quality curriculum system and teaching services, which compete for educational content and services; and a high-quality education in Pratt & Whitney, which relies on technological products, " the person in charge of the homework assignment told China News Weekly, at the same time, the flow capacity is also a moat.

How many of the 200 million students will be left behind? According to the survey, half of the students asked if they could take online classes in the future, Li Zhong said, "This is a surprise to us because online training is not comparable to offline training. Online institutions are no better than offline ones. Compared to offline giants, it's not worth mentioning. On the bright side, I think in the next two to three years, the two will be equal. "

Before the outbreak, online education for out-of-school training was not strong enough. Frost Sullivan, an international consulting firm, reports that China's education market is more than trillion yuan, with the out-of-school tutoring and exam preparation market increasing from 412.3 billion yuan in 2013 to 632.5 billion yuan in 2017, the online off-campus training market grew from 32.9 billion yuan to 96.4 billion yuan, accounting for less than a fifth of the total.

Under the epidemic, online education has become one of the few "beneficiary industries" , with a surprising wave of development dividends. Officials in charge of the good future said that students and parents in third-and fourth-tier cities who previously knew little or could not accept online education are expected to gradually begin to accept live online teaching through this epidemic, accelerate the attempt of online education products.

In addition to off-campus training facilities, there is a growing interest in how public schools are integrated with the Internet. There is a famous "Jobs's question" in education: Why is it that computers have changed almost everything, but have had surprisingly little impact on schooling?

Online education in public schools has not been going well. An education professional, who asked not to be named, told China News weekly that the public system actually spends a lot of money on internet system applications, but it is still in the stage of recording and on demand, "Online" and "education" don't really mix.

"The traditional informatization of education in schools has exposed many drawbacks under the epidemic, and investment is more useful than useful, " said Zhu Guoping, managing director of thunderstorm capital, to increase the access of quality online education enterprises to schools.

"for education informatization and online teaching, the epidemic may be an opportunity to turn bad things into educational change, " Zhu Yongxin said in a recent post.

"everyone is using it, which is a good thing, but there are many problems: the educational resources provided at the national level may be relatively single and insufficient, many schools and teachers are not ready, and the equipment and internet speed of many students, especially poor families, are big problems, " Zhu Yongxin told China News Weekly, in the past, people used to rely more on schools, on the regular education system, but now it seems that online education is likely to become a very important part of education, "not mainstream, but at least one of the important roles. ".
